metadata.title: Stock Fundamental Analysis: EDA of SEC’s quarterly data summary | by Vaclav Dekanovsky | Towards Data Science
metadata.h1: Stock Fundamental Analysis: EDA of SEC’s quarterly data summary
metadata.description: Many investors consider fundamental analysis as their secret weapon to beat the stock market. You can perform it using many methods, but one thing they have in common. They all need data about…

all_paragraphs: Many investors consider fundamental analysis as their secret weapon to beat the stock market. You can perform it using many methods, but one thing they have in common. They all need data about companies’ financial statements.

Luckily all stocks traded on US stock markets must quarterly report to the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC). Every quarter SEC prepares a comfortable CSV package to help all the investors in their quest for the investment opportunity. Let’s explore how to get valuable insights from these .csv files.
In this tutorial, we will use python’s pandas library which ideal for parsing CSV files, and we will learn how to:
We will process the data and:
As usual, you can follow the code in the notebook shared on GitHub.

There doesn’t seem to be any problem. You simply download the quarterly package from the SEC dataset page, you sort the values from the financial statements in descending order and pick the stocks on the top. The reality isn’t that straightforward. Let’s have a look and explore 45.55MB big zip file with all SEC filings for the first quarter of 2020.
The package for every quarter contains 5 files. Here’s an example of 2020 Q1:
This article will only deal with the submission master because it contains more than enough information for one article. Follow-up story will examine the data in more detail. Let’s begin.
In the first quarter of 2020, the companies have submitted 13560 files and the sub.txt gathers 36 columns about them.
I always start with a simple function that reviews each column of the data frame, checks the percentage of empty values, and how many unique values appear in the columns.
Let me highlight a few important columns in the SEC submission master.

Based on the analysis, we see that the 2020Q1 submission contains 23 unique types of financial reports. Investors' primary interest lies in the 10-K report, which covers the annual performance of the publically traded company. Because this report is expectedly delivered only once a year, important is also 10-Q report showing quarterly changes in the company’s financials.
Let’s see which forms are the most common in the dataset. Plotting of the form types in the 2020Q1 will show this picture:

The dataset contains over 7000 8-K reports notifying about important events like agreements, layoffs, usage of material, modification of shareholder rights, change in the senior positions, and more (see SEC’s guideline). Since they are the most common we should spend some time exploring them.
Filtering only the 8-K forms we see that the dataset contains 7502 records of this type.
If we merge with the num.txt containing the detailed financial numbers we only get 2894 lines. Some records don’t seem to have the details.
On top of that, these records cover only 20 unique reports (each report is identified by adsh number).

That is because the num.txt contain only financial details, while most 8-K describe the events in words. Only rare events like 0001262976–20–000015, a special case which declares an extra financial statement as part of the 8-K report.
8-K describes the events in plain text, which is not part of the dump. Details only appear if it includes a financial statement, which is rare

We rarely see any data in the num.txt related to 8-K forms. Let’s chart all the form types to see if other filing are different. We will left-join the num.txt to thesub.txt and use the indicator parameter to see which adsh keys appear in both.
When we have joined the two files we can see that only the 8-K and 8-K/A miss financial details, which is perfect, because now we are going to explore the annual 10-K and quarterly 10-Q statements

Out of the 7502 8-K filings only 20 contains additional information in the SEC’s quarterly data dump, which doesn’t give many benefits. Let’s switch our focus to more interesting submission types — annual reports 10-Ks and quarterly report 10-Qs and then we will briefly look on the other forms.

SEC released the dataset at the beginning of April 2020, so we have a high chance to see some annual reports dated 2019–12–31 in the records. If we filter only 10-K and 10-Q we see that really most of the data in the 2020Q1 dump are annual reports.
But do all the companies report Annual statement on the last day of the year?

The dataset contains columns fy and fp which denotes what fiscal year and quarter the financial statement represents. We plot the chart of the most typical. (see the full notebook for code, section “Fiscal Year”)

It reveals one interesting fact that 2020Q1 data contains quarters 2 and 3 of 2020 fiscal year. How is it possible that in the first quarter we already know the financial results of the summer and autumn?
Let’s look at one of these financial statements for Rexnord corporation.

Fiscal years presented in this report prior to and including fiscal year 2020 refer to the period from April 1 until March 31 of the corresponding calendar year. For example, our fiscal year 2020, or fiscal 2020, means the period from April 1, 2019 to March 31, 2020. — Rexnord corporation

The fiscal year doesn’t have to mirror the calendar one. There are companies that end the fiscal year 2020 in January and most of data fell into 2019. It means that the fiscal revenues of one company are not comparable with others.

To align the prices with fundamental characteristics, we have to be sure when the revenue was gained, and the cash flowed in. What variable do we use to find out the real time frame of the financial data? It’s another variable in the dataset named period . Let’s look at the plot.

I’ve utilized higher-level API of Plotly, so-called Plotly.express. It is very powerful with datasets, however, it struggles with the subplots of different types, like bar chart and sunburst chart in this case.
The sunburst chart is a useful alternative to the pie chart in case you want to show details of the categories.

We can see that most of the statements fall into the expected period at the end of 2019 and the beginning of 2020. There are also some filing from Sep, Oct, and Nov 2019. Why weren’t they part of the previous dump in 2019Q4?

Note: The periods seem to end on the last day of the month, but that is caused by the rounding introduced by SEC. There are companies, like John Deere which use 52/53 week fiscal year and their accounting year ends on 2019 Nov-3 (see SEC filing). Most companies, nevertheless, submit their statements by the month ends.

The SEC has a deadline of 40–45 days for quarterly and 60–90 days for annual statements (see SEC guideline). 60 days is for smaller companies and 3 months for the large behemoths. It means that at the beginning of January when 2019Q4 dump was released some companies haven’t uploaded October, November, or even September data. That is why they appear in the first dump of 2020.
Let’s explore if everyone manages to meet these deadlines. We compare the value of accepted (when the data was accepted by SEC )with the period when the fiscal period ended.
We look on the basic statistics parameters:
The quickest accountants deliver the statements within 11 days, but both mean and median are nearing 60 days. Using Plotly's ability to create histograms, we can examine the usual delivery time.

Do you notice the sudden drop in the number of submitted forms after 90 days? It acknowledges that most companies can meet the deadline and only a few submissions come late. There can also be some corrections, which we explore in the following section.
Typical annual report has more than 50 pages. See Amazon’s 10-K

We would expect that each company reports exactly one report in each quarter, but a diligent analyst would double-check on that. We groupby the companies’ unique cik number and plot how many enterprises post single submission and if there are some who fill in more.
Then we can create a plot directly from pandas if you set the
We would expect that all cik ‘s have reported only one submission, and for most of the companies, this is true. There were however some which have posted more records.

Why do companies do this? Are these errors or corrections to the previous submissions? Are they splitting the information into multiple filings? We won’t know unless we look at the examples of multiple submissions.
We filter the rows of the duplicates:

The code above shows 321 rows, ordered by the cik and the period and the brief look will tell us that really, most of the companies are submitting some historical corrections. The company with cik=1191334 seems to report whole history containing 24 quarterly and 9 annual reports, but most send only one or two additional filings.
Spot check didn’t reveal any company which would send two fillings for the same period. Can we prove that they really don’t exist?
The check for grouped cik&period combination discovered that there are some companies which uploaded to SEC the data for the same period twice.
Let’s looks at them, by using groupby as a filter:
The detailed look demonstrates that they differ in either filed , accepted or both.

Duplicated lines are a curse of each dataset. They cause many problems because they skew the metrics, pollute machine learning models, and multiply with each join. Once we discover them, we should immediately take a decision on how to remove them.

In our case, we will accept only the forms which were filled in later (higher filed ) and in case all records have it equal, we take the one with newer accepted . Pandas’s .cumcount() function will help us with the task. It’s equivalent to SQL’s ROW_COUNT() and we will only pick the first occurrence of each record. Detailed steps are:
See the full code with a detailed break up on the Github.
A similar algorithm will help us get only the latest submission provided in 2020Q1:

10-K and Q are mandatory for all US-based companies traded on the stock markets. But SEC collects information about foreign enterprises which benefit from the US markets. They have to send the financial statement under 20-F and 40-F forms. How do they differ?
Let’s use the columns countryba and cityba which hold the information about the registrant’s business address. We turn this information into an address.
Having latitudes and longitudes of the places, we can display them on the world map. Plotly’s .scatter_geo() is the type of chart we need:

Do you want to try yourself? Nothing is easier. SEC has recently published the 2020Q2 data. Download them, unzip and run the scripts from this notebook to see whether the structure of the forms has changed in the second quarter.

In this article, we have reviewed the submission types provided in the quarterly SEC data dump. We have seen that the most common 8-Ks doesn’t have additional information in the dump. So we focussed on the annual and quarterly statements and explored that these appear in the dataset up to 180 days after the submission. Mostly the companies report one statement in the quarter, but we have seen some historical filings and some duplicates.

By removing the duplicates we have prepared the dataset for the next step in the analysis —exploring the financials. But that is enough information for this article, and we will talk about it next time.
